The National Human Rights Commission in Kano State has stated that it received 52 cases of human rights abuses in January 2022. The State Coordinator, Shehu Abdullahi, noted in an interview with the NAN in Kano, on Wednesday. Abdullahi said that the commission had attended to 35 cases out of the 52 cases, while 17 are pending. According to him, most of the cases were related to issues on domestic violence, forceful marriage, marriage, and parental responsibility. “Out of the 52 cases received, 40 were on the abandonment of wife and family; access to children, while the remaining were on domestic violence and forceful marriage,” he said. Abdullahi said the commission had also mediated on matters among couples and families, adding that some of the cases had been referred to courts after thorough investigations. He urged the state government to provide a more enabling environment through the enforcement of existing laws, provision of additional policies, and legal framework. He also urged all stakeholders to guarantee the security of women and children at home, schools, and working places. NAN